8 An Act relating to community health workers; creating
the Oklahoma Community Health Workers Act; defining
9 terms; directing establishment of certificate; making
certification voluntary; authorizing certified
10 community health workers to perform certain
functions; providing eligibility requirements for
11 voluntary certification; requiring and authorizing
promulgation of certain rules; directing
12 establishment of certain fees; providing for
codification; and providing an effective date.
13
14
15 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
16 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
17 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1280 of Title 59, unless there
18 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
19 This act shall be known and may be cited as the "Oklahoma
20 Community Health Workers Act".
21 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
22 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1280.1 of Title 59, unless there
23 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
24 As used in the Oklahoma Community Health Workers Act:
ENGR. H. B. NO. 1831 Page 1

1 1. "Certified community health worker" means a community health
2 worker to whom the State Department of Health has issued a
3 certificate to practice as a certified community health worker in
4 this state;
5 2. "Community health worker" means a frontline health worker
6 who has a shared understanding of and is a trusted member of the
7 community being served;
8 3. "Core competencies" means the knowledge and skills a
9 certified community health worker is expected to demonstrate in
10 order to carry out the mission and goals of the profession as
11 defined by the Department through the promulgation of administrative
12 regulations in accordance with state guidelines; and
13 4. "Department" means the State Department of Health as
14 established to direct guidance, in collaboration with the State
15 Community Health Worker Association or Advisory Committee, in
16 relation to community health worker training, certification, and
17 recertification protocols.
18 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
19 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1280.2 of Title 59, unless there
20 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
21 A. The State Department of Health shall establish a certificate
22 for community health workers. This certification shall be
23 voluntary.
24 B. A certified community health worker may:
ENGR. H. B. NO. 1831 Page 2

1 1. Serve as a liaison between health and social services and
2 the community, including faith-based organizations, to facilitate
3 access to services and improve the quality and cultural competence
4 of service delivery;
5 2. Assist in identifying and communicating gaps in current
6 community and health care resources; and
7 3. Build individual and community capacity by increasing health
8 knowledge and self-sufficiency through a range of activities such as
9 outreach, community education, coaching, mentoring, social support,
10 and advocacy, including efforts within faith-based settings.
11 SECTION 4. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
12 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1280.3 of Title 59, unless there
13 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
14 Eligibility to apply for voluntary certification, in order to be
15 eligible to apply for community health worker certification, an
16 individual shall:
17 1. Be a legal United States resident;
18 2. Be a resident of Oklahoma;
19 3. Be at least eighteen (18) years of age; and
20 4. Provide evidence to the Department of his or her work
21 experience as a community health worker, demonstrating a minimum of
22 one thousand (1,000) practical hours and recommendation from a
23 supervising provider, shall be considered certified under this work
24 experience pathway provision.
